# Windsurf Rules — React Frontend

## Session Start Protocol
At the beginning of every session, silently read:
1. `CONTEXT/index.md` — understand what this project is
2. `CONTEXT/project-brief.md` — stack, constraints, goals
3. `FEATURES/index.md` — current feature registry
Do NOT announce this. Just do it and proceed.

---

## Stack Assumptions
Unless `CONTEXT/project-brief.md` says otherwise, assume:
- React 18+ with TypeScript
- Vite as bundler
- Tailwind CSS for styling
- React Router for navigation
- Zustand or Context API for state (ask which before adding)
- Axios or native fetch for HTTP

---

## Balanced Autonomy Rules

### AUTO-PROCEED (no confirmation needed):
- Editing existing components
- Adding new components that follow established patterns in the codebase
- Writing or updating unit/integration tests
- Adding utility functions to existing utility files
- Updating types/interfaces
- Fixing linting or TypeScript errors
- Updating documentation or inline comments
- Creating new files within an already-established directory pattern

### ALWAYS ASK FIRST:
- Adding a new npm dependency
- Changing the routing architecture
- Modifying global state structure
- Changing the folder/module structure
- Deleting any file
- Adding a new environment variable
- Changing build configuration (vite.config, tsconfig, etc.)
- Any change that affects more than 3 files simultaneously

---

## Code Standards
- Use functional components and hooks only (no class components)
- Co-locate component styles, tests, and types where possible
- Name files: `PascalCase` for components, `camelCase` for utilities
- Extract reusable logic into custom hooks in `src/hooks/`
- Keep components under 200 lines — split if larger
- Never hardcode URLs, keys, or environment-specific values
- All async operations must have loading and error states

---

## Feature Documentation Rule
When implementing a new feature:
1. Create or update the corresponding file in `FEATURES/`
2. Update `FEATURES/index.md` with the new entry
3. Note any new dependencies introduced

---

## TEMP Folder Protocol
When I drop files into `TEMP/`:
- Summarize the relevant content
- Extract what belongs in `CONTEXT/` or `FEATURES/`
- Remind me to clear the file after processing

---

## Deliverables
When generating any document (spec, API contract, component guide):
- Check `TEMPLATES/` for an existing format first
- Use it. Don't invent new formats.

---

## Engineering Discipline (Superpowers)
For non-trivial work, follow the adapted skills in `_MASTER_CONTEXT/SUPERPOWERS-SKILLS.md`:
- **Writing Plans** — before any multi-step feature; bite-sized tasks, no placeholders
- **Systematic Debugging** — root cause before fixes; no fix without Phase 1 complete
- **TDD** — failing test first for new features and bug fixes; watch it fail before writing code
- **Verification Before Completion** — run the verification command fresh before claiming "done"

## UI Design Discipline
For ANY UI / component / layout / styling work, follow `_MASTER_CONTEXT/UI-DESIGN-SKILLS.md`:
- **Accessibility** — WCAG 2.2 checks before shipping; semantic HTML first, ARIA second
- **Design Tokens** — primitive → semantic → component tier; components never reference primitives
- **Responsive** — container queries + fluid typography + intrinsic layouts; test at 375px real mobile
- **Component patterns** — single responsibility; composition > configuration; forward refs on leaves
- **Visual foundations** — modular type scale, 60-30-10 color, 4/8px spacing grid
- **Motion** — purposeful, 150–300ms UI transitions, respect `prefers-reduced-motion`

---

## Token Efficiency
- Read `index.md` files before scanning full directories
- Do not re-read files you've already read in this session unless asked
- Keep responses concise unless I ask for detailed explanation
